><p>Giving evidence for a second day, the student, who is gay, dismissed as \"pure fiction\" a claim that he kissed Evans before they went to the MP's bedroom to have sex.</p><p>He denied that he asked Evans whether he should follow him into his bedroom, telling jurors that the MP \"escorted\" him into the room using his arm. Asked by Wright why he did not refuse to enter the MP's bedroom, the student said: \"That was my missed opportunity. That was fairly critical\".</p><p>When they were in bed the student tried to fend off Evans by saying he was tired and rolling over as the MP tried to grope and kiss him, the court heard.</p><p>Wright, for Evans, questioned why the younger man returned to the bed three times if he did not consent to the sexual touching. \"You haven't said no. You haven't said leave me alone. You haven't said I don't want to do this,\" said Wright.</p><p>\"I didn't do anything flirtatious at all,\" the complainant replied.</p><p>\"Having got into bed it became clear to you within a very short space of time that there were sexual overtures being made towards you and you didn't say stop it. You didn't then say no. You didn't physically push him away. And thereafter on three occasions you leave the bed and go to the bathroom and on all occasions you return to the same bedroom and get back into bed with the man?\"</p><p>\"Yes,\" the alleged victim replied.</p><p>Asked whether he did anything more than tell the MP he was tired during this episode, he said: \"Roll over a bit more, try brush it off.\"</p><p>The student also denied being openly flirtatious with Evans at a Christmas party at the RAC club in London six months before the alleged rape.</p><p>Wright suggested the young man had his hands on the MP's chest and thighs and was looking longingly into his eyes when the pair chatted at the party. \"That's just ridiculous,\" the complainant said. \"I've never been like that towards Nigel, ever.\"</p><p>The student said he assumed it would just be hims