d thinktanks had been looking for measures to help ease the cost of housing and get more people, especially the young and long-term unemployed, into jobs. However the speech focused on a core Tory audience of pensioners and those approaching retirement.</p><p>Institute for Fiscal Studies research shows savers – who got measures ranging from more generous Isas to state-backed bonds for the elderly – are more likely to be in the wealthiest half of the population.</p><p>In contrast, the poorest half are often families already in debt or saving nothing at all. Young people, many saddled with student debts, also barely save and tend not to make a start until their 30s or 40s, accumulating more as they get older.</p><p>\"The chancellor talked about making, doing and saving. This budget needs to work for those who are making do and can't save,\" said Gillian Guy, chief executive of Citizens Advice.</p><p>The young were mentioned just once in the chancellor's speech, when he extended a scheme to help small businesses employ an extra 100,000 apprentices.</p><p>Labour had feared Osborne could match their pledge of a guaranteed job for all unemployed young people. There was also talk of Osborne expanding tax breaks for employers hiring under-21s to those taking on workers under 25. Neither of these policies materialised.</p><p>The Joseph Rowntree Foundation also pointed out that the budget delivered next to nothing for the lowest earners or those who do not have jobs. \"This is a budget for the people who already have,\" said the charity's chief executive, Julia Unwin.</p><p>Measures to ease the rising cost of housing, especially for the younger generation, were also notably absent, except for the confirmation of a garden city of Ebbsfleet, which has already been announced, and an expansion of the Help to Buy scheme – an Osborne scheme from earlier in the parliament.</p><p>Critics argue Help to Buy is actually fuelling higher house prices, disadvantaging future first-time buyers, while Labour claims the 15,000 houses planned for the new town in Kent fall far short of what is&nbsp;needed.</p><p>\"We think the budget is a missed opportunity,\" said David Orr, chief executive of the National Housing Federation. \"Measures like Help to Buy are likely to stimulate demand for housing but the budget does not go far enough to boost the supply of homes needed to meet that demand.\"</p><p>Coalition ministers have repeatedly attempted to argue that their priority is tax cuts for the lowest earners by raising the level at which people start paying income tax from £10,000 to £10,500 – a policy originally championed by the Lib Dems. However, those earning below this threshold miss out on the tax cut.</p><p>\"Higher earners stand to gain up to five times more than the poorest from changes to personal tax allowances,\" said Puja Darbari, director of strategy at Barnardo's.</p><p>There was also little to address concerns about the rising cost of living, which was the first thing noted by Labour leader Ed Miliband when he stood up to respond to the budget. \"The chancellor spoke for nearly an hour. But he did not mention one central fact: the working people of Britain are worse off under the Tories,\" he said.</p><p>Osborne did freeze a green tax to save households £15 a year on their energy bills, while the 1p off beer duty, freeze on Scottish whisky and cider duty, and cut in the bingo levy will also provide modest help. However, the taxes that most affect the lowest earners – VAT and the lower level at which people start paying National Insurance compared with income tax – were unchanged.</p><p>There was also little detail on where a future axe would fall on benefits or how further public spending decisions will be made. The chancellor confirmed he would bring in a welfare cap of £119.5bn, with the state pension and unemployment benefits exempted from this. However, there was no certainty about how the cuts will be distributed.</p>","headline":"Chancel