Osborne tried accelerated fiscal reduction and saw that it didn't work. In fact, it made things worse. And though he said he was still implementing it, behind the scenes he was taking his foot off the accelerator.\"</p><p>According to Portes, the change of tack is why we now have growth and a feelgood factor that could prove to be sustainable for the rest of the decade.</p><p>However, Osborne needs to continue squeezing his budget and from this year has switched almost exclusively to achieving that aim with welfare spending cuts. There are many on the Tory backbenches squaring up for a fight – but just as many who fear a return to the riots that spread quickly from London to Salford, Nottingham and Bristol three years ago.</p><p>Osborne has balked at spelling out where the cuts would fall, though there are a few signals. Since 2011, attacks by public-sector unions have been muted once it became obvious that grade rises would be allowed even if annual pay increases were frozen.</p><p>Now there are large numbers of public-sector workers looking forward to grade freezes as well. Public-sector pension savings have caused huge upset. Osborne's decision to spend the money instead of saving for the moment, in 20 or 30 years, when funds are needed for pensions, will only make public-sector workers even angrier.</p><p>Councils are about to suffer another funding cut, one that will leave them 20% worse off between this year and the year after the election. The Home Office is staring at further cuts before 2015-16, as are most other departments.</p><p>As the Institute for Fiscal Studies – a respected financial thinktank – has pointed out repeatedly in the last two years, the government's insistence on protecting health and schools spending, as well as fencing off the international development budget, means cuts of 40% in many other departments.</p><p>Will these cuts be accepted without protest? It is not just Conservative backbenchers who are concerned. City economists such as Michael Saunders at Citi are sceptical too.</p><p>Politically, cuts will not only affect the low-paid and benefit claimants. It will also fuel the resentment felt by many Ukip supporters at cuts in defence spending. The department was allowed to roll over its savings from the previous year into 2013-14 as part of the 2013 budget. This one-year gift is likely to be forgotten as the service comes to rely on the Territorial Army to make up for further cuts in professional staff.</p><p>Preferably, the government would enjoy higher tax receipts to balance spending with income, but it is a measure of the lack of confidence in Whitehall at the UK's capacity to generate income that it is relying on spending cuts.</p><p>However, property remains a sure fire winner, at least in the boom times. Stamp duty on house sales is set to almost double in the next four years from £9.5bn to £18.1bn. Income tax will only inch higher in that time and corporation tax by a mere £4.5bn to £45.9bn.</p><p>It's partly why the UK's annual spending deficits have stayed higher than our continental partners. And its why S&amp;P remains wary of restoring the UK to its former AAA status, unlike Fitch and Moody's.</p>","headline":"Osborne's focus on public-sector cuts won't impress ratings agencies","trailText":"<p>Chancellor is focusing almost exclusively on welfare spending cuts to squeeze his budget</p>","thumbnail":"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2014/3/19/1395264219906/AAA-credit-rating-006.jpg","wordcount":"692","liveBloggingNow":"false","commentCloseDate":"2014-03-22T21:34:00Z"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2014/mar/19/george-osborne-public-sector-spending-cuts-credit-ratings-agencies","apiUrl":"http://beta.content.guardianapis.com/uk-news/2014/mar/19/george-osborne-public-sector-spending-cuts-credit-ratings-agencies","tags":[{"id":"uk-news/budget-2014","webTitle":"Budget 2014","type":"keyword","sectionId":"uk-news","sectionName":"UK news","webUrl":"h